Avusa, Capitec Bank, Jubilee Platinum: South African Equity Market Preview

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-03-29T22:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-29/avusa-capitec-bank-jubilee-platinum-s-african-stock.html
The following stocks may rise or
fall in  South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last close.  South Africa’s FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index rose 340.89,
or 1.1 percent, to 31,718.01 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg.  Avusa Ltd. (AVU)  (AVU): South Africa’s second-largest media
company has received a 2.7 billion rand ($393 million) or 26
rand-a-share offer from Capitau Holdings, a private equity firm.
Avusa declined 20 cents, or 0.8 percent, to 24.80 rand.
 Mvelaphanda Group Ltd. (MVG)  , an investment holding company
with a 25.5 percent stake in Avusa, advanced 19 cents, or 6.4
percent, to 3.18 rand.  Cape Empowerment Ltd. (CAP)  : The investment holding
company said it has swung to a profit per share of 3.4 cents in
the year ended December, from a loss of 1.4 cents a share a year
earlier. The stock was unchanged at 23 cents.  Capitec Bank Holdings Ltd. (CPI)  : The second-largest
South African provider of unsecured loans publishes its earnings
for the year ended February. The company said on Feb. 8 that it
expects its earnings to rise by as much as 50 percent when
compared to a year earlier. Capitec increased 1.01 rand, or 0.6
percent, to 170 rand.  The  Don Group (DON)  Ltd: The hotel group lowered its
loss to 5.2 million rand in the first half through December,
from 11.5 million rand a year earlier. The shares declined 3
cents, or 13 percent, to 20 cents.  Jubilee Platinum Plc (JLP)  : The mineral exploration
company said its loss per share after one-time items narrowed to
0.76 British pence, from a restated 0.81 pence a year earlier.
Jubilee fell 3 cents, or 1 percent, to 3 rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
